------------------------------------------------------------
1. Opening Context ‚Äì Why This Lecture Exists
------------------------------------------------------------

The instructor begins by clearly stating that:

‚Ä¢ Big-O notation
‚Ä¢ Big-Œ© notation
‚Ä¢ Big-Œò notation

have already been **completed properly** in previous lectures.

Only **two notations are left**:
‚Ä¢ Small-o
‚Ä¢ Small-omega (œâ)

He honestly tells students:

‚ÄúThese are not very important for exams,
but you should NOT skip them completely.‚Äù

Why?
Because they give **conceptual depth** and help you
understand **dominance vs strict dominance**.

He also promises:
Today, he will explain **why Œò exists**
and **why small-Œ∏ DOES NOT exist**.


------------------------------------------------------------
2. Board Setup (Image Explanation)
------------------------------------------------------------

On the board, the instructor writes:

f(n) = 3n + 2     (underlined)

On the right side of the board:
‚Ä¢ O(n)
‚Ä¢ O(n¬≤)
‚Ä¢ O(n¬≥)
‚Ä¢ O(n log n)

These are written with arrows, circles, and question marks.

üîç Meaning of the drawing:
The teacher is visually showing that **one function can satisfy
multiple Big-O bounds**, because Big-O allows ‚Äú‚â• or =‚Äù.

This visual directly contrasts with **Small-o**, where equality is forbidden.


------------------------------------------------------------
3. Revisiting Big-O (Very Briefly, for Contrast)
------------------------------------------------------------

In Big-O, we say:

f(n) = O(g(n))
if there exists **AT LEAST ONE positive constant C**
such that:

f(n) ‚â§ C¬∑g(n)  for all n ‚â• n‚ÇÄ

This is why:
‚Ä¢ f(n) = 3n + 2
‚Ä¢ can be O(n)
‚Ä¢ can be O(n log n)
‚Ä¢ can be O(n¬≤)
‚Ä¢ can even be O(n¬≥)

Because Big-O is an **upper bound**, not a tight bound.


------------------------------------------------------------
4. Introducing Small-o (Core Definition)
------------------------------------------------------------

Now the instructor switches tone and says:

‚ÄúNow focus carefully.
Here is where students usually make mistakes.‚Äù

Definition (spoken slowly):

f(n) = o(g(n))
IF
for **EVERY positive constant C**
there exists a value n‚ÇÄ
such that for all n ‚â• n‚ÇÄ,

f(n) < C¬∑g(n)     (STRICT inequality)

Key stress points (repeated multiple times in lecture):

1Ô∏è‚É£ **For EVERY positive constant**
   ‚Äì not at least one  
   ‚Äì every possible positive real number  
   ‚Äì 0.1, 0.001, 100, 1/100000, anything  

2Ô∏è‚É£ **Strictly less than**
   ‚Äì NOT ‚â§  
   ‚Äì equality is NOT allowed  

3Ô∏è‚É£ After some n‚ÇÄ, this must hold forever  


------------------------------------------------------------
5. Core Intuition (Teacher‚Äôs Main Explanation)
------------------------------------------------------------

The teacher explains this intuition in multiple ways.

He says:

‚ÄúIn Small-o, constants don‚Äôt matter anymore.‚Äù

Why?

Because if **even after multiplying g(n) by a very small constant**,
g(n) is still bigger than f(n),
then f(n) is **fundamentally smaller**.

This means:
‚Ä¢ The dominance is not due to constants
‚Ä¢ The dominance is due to growth rate


------------------------------------------------------------
6. Height Analogy (Board Drawing Explanation)
------------------------------------------------------------

On the board, the teacher draws two circles:

‚Ä¢ One circle lower
‚Ä¢ One circle much higher

He draws arrows:
‚Ä¢ Try to pull the higher one down
‚Ä¢ Try to push it up

Explanation:

If one function is already much larger in growth,
then:
‚Ä¢ Making the constant smaller does not help
‚Ä¢ Making the constant bigger does not matter

The taller person always remains taller.

That is Small-o.


------------------------------------------------------------
7. Second (Easier) Definition of Small-o
------------------------------------------------------------

Now the teacher writes a new definition:

f(n) = o(g(n))
IFF

lim (n ‚Üí ‚àû) [ f(n) / g(n) ] = 0

He explicitly says:

‚ÄúThis definition is VERY EASY and VERY IMPORTANT.‚Äù

Why?

Because:
‚Ä¢ No constants
‚Ä¢ No guessing C
‚Ä¢ Just check the limit

If the ratio goes to zero,
then f(n) is negligible compared to g(n).


------------------------------------------------------------
8. Board Question 1 (From Image)
------------------------------------------------------------

Question written on the board:

f(n) = 3n + 2   ‚Üí TRUE?

Options:
a) f(n) = o(n¬≤)        ‚úì
b) f(n) = o(n log n)   ‚úì
c) f(n) = o(n¬≥)        ‚úì
d) f(n) = o(n)         ‚úó

Now the teacher explains **each option verbally**.


------------------------------------------------------------
9. Option (a): f(n) = o(n¬≤)
------------------------------------------------------------

Check the limit:

(3n + 2) / n¬≤ ‚Üí 0

n¬≤ grows much faster than n.

So YES:
f(n) = o(n¬≤)

Teacher‚Äôs money analogy:
‚ÄúIf you have one crore squared money,
then 3 crore + 2 rupees means nothing.‚Äù


------------------------------------------------------------
10. Option (b): f(n) = o(n log n)
------------------------------------------------------------

Check the limit:

(3n + 2) / (n log n)
= (3 + 2/n) / log n ‚Üí 0

Because log n ‚Üí ‚àû.

So YES:
f(n) = o(n log n)


------------------------------------------------------------
11. Option (c): f(n) = o(n¬≥)
------------------------------------------------------------

Same logic:

(3n + 2) / n¬≥ ‚Üí 0

So YES:
f(n) = o(n¬≥)


------------------------------------------------------------
12. Option (d): f(n) = o(n) ‚ùå
------------------------------------------------------------

Check the limit:

(3n + 2) / n ‚Üí 3

Limit ‚â† 0.

So this FAILS.

Teacher‚Äôs warning:

‚ÄúIf someone chooses a very small constant,
you will not be able to prove it.‚Äù

Hence:
f(n) ‚â† o(n)


------------------------------------------------------------
13. Important Relationship (Board Arrows)
------------------------------------------------------------

The teacher draws arrows showing:

Small-o  ‚áí  Big-O   (ALWAYS)

But:
Big-O  ‚áè  Small-o

Why?

Because:
‚Ä¢ Big-O allows equality
‚Ä¢ Small-o forbids equality


------------------------------------------------------------
14. Introducing Small-Omega (œâ)
------------------------------------------------------------

Now the teacher flips the logic.

Definition:

f(n) = œâ(g(n))
IF
for **EVERY positive constant C**
there exists n‚ÇÄ such that for all n ‚â• n‚ÇÄ,

f(n) > C¬∑g(n)   (STRICT)

Again:
‚Ä¢ EVERY constant
‚Ä¢ STRICT inequality


------------------------------------------------------------
15. Limit Definition of Small-Omega
------------------------------------------------------------

Second definition:

f(n) = œâ(g(n))
IFF

lim (n ‚Üí ‚àû) [ g(n) / f(n) ] = 0

Meaning:
f(n) grows so fast that g(n) becomes negligible.


------------------------------------------------------------
16. Why Equality Is NOT Allowed (Critical Insight)
------------------------------------------------------------

Example discussed verbally:

f(n) = 3n + 2  
g(n) = n  

Even though f(n) > n for large n,
you CANNOT say f(n) = œâ(n).

Why?

Because:
For large constants (like C = 10000),
the inequality fails.

Since definition says:
‚Äúfor EVERY constant‚Äù,
even ONE failure breaks everything.


------------------------------------------------------------
17. Why Small-Theta Does NOT Exist
------------------------------------------------------------

This is the conceptual climax.

Big-Œò says:
C‚ÇÅ¬∑g(n) ‚â§ f(n) ‚â§ C‚ÇÇ¬∑g(n)

Equality allowed.

If we try to define Small-Œò,
we would need:

‚Ä¢ f(n) strictly bigger than g(n)
‚Ä¢ AND strictly smaller than g(n)
‚Ä¢ For EVERY constant

This is **logically impossible**.

Hence:
‚ùå Small-Œò does not exist.

That is why we never define it.


------------------------------------------------------------
18. Final Summary (Teacher‚Äôs Own Words, Structured)
------------------------------------------------------------

Small-o:
‚Ä¢ f(n) is STRICTLY smaller than g(n)
‚Ä¢ Ratio ‚Üí 0

Small-Omega:
‚Ä¢ f(n) is STRICTLY larger than g(n)
‚Ä¢ Reverse ratio ‚Üí 0

Big-O / Big-Œ©:
‚Ä¢ Equality allowed

Constants:
‚Ä¢ Become meaningless at infinity

Growth rate:
‚Ä¢ Everything


------------------------------------------------------------
19. Lecture Closure
------------------------------------------------------------

The instructor concludes:

‚ÄúAll five asymptotic notations are now complete.‚Äù

Next lecture:
‚Ä¢ Properties
‚Ä¢ Symmetry
‚Ä¢ Transitivity

He encourages students to **think**, not memorize,
because algorithm analysis improves only by thinking.

